Title
AWS Infrastructure Analyzer → Inventory + Diagrams + Well-Architected Review + Security + FinOps + Remediation Plan

Context
You are operating under the active skill: aws_hyper_ultimate_architect.
I will provide an AWS infrastructure codebase and/or exports (Terraform / CloudFormation / CDK outputs / account structure notes).
Your job is to analyze the infrastructure end-to-end and produce a complete architecture understanding, diagrams, and actionable improvements.

Task
1) Determine the infrastructure definition scope:
   - Identify IaC type(s): Terraform, CloudFormation, CDK, SAM, Serverless Framework, raw AWS CLI scripts.
   - Identify environments: dev/stage/prod, regions, accounts, and whether this is multi-account (Organizations/Control Tower).
   - Identify modules/stacks boundaries and ownership areas.

2) Build a comprehensive inventory (grounded in code/files):
   A) Accounts & governance
      - AWS Organizations structure (if present), SCPs, OU layout, Control Tower baseline assumptions
      - IAM Identity Center (SSO) presence, account vending, guardrails
   B) Identity & access
      - IAM users/roles/policies (principle-of-least-privilege assessment)
      - trust policies, cross-account access patterns
      - secrets: Secrets Manager/SSM Parameter Store usage (metadata only, no secret values)
   C) Networking
      - VPCs, subnets, route tables, IGW/NAT, TGW, VPC peering, PrivateLink
      - on-prem connectivity: VPN/DX (as inferred)
      - DNS: Route53 zones, resolver rules (if present)
   D) Edge & traffic management
      - CloudFront, ALB/NLB, API Gateway, WAF, Shield, Global Accelerator
   E) Compute & orchestration
      - EC2/ASG, ECS/EKS/Fargate, Lambda, Batch, App Runner, Step Functions
      - deployment patterns: blue/green, canary, rolling
   F) Data & storage
      - S3 buckets posture (encryption, public access blocks), EBS/EFS/FSx
      - RDS/Aurora/DynamoDB/Redshift/ElastiCache/Neptune etc.
      - backup posture: AWS Backup, snapshots, PITR, cross-region replication
   G) Observability & audit
      - CloudWatch (logs/metrics/alarms), X-Ray, OpenTelemetry (if present)
      - CloudTrail org trails, Config, log archives
   H) Security services & posture
      - GuardDuty, Security Hub, Inspector, Macie, Detective
      - KMS key strategy, rotation, encryption coverage
      - incident response readiness & logging immutability
   I) CI/CD & IaC pipelines
      - CodePipeline/CodeBuild/CodeDeploy, GitHub Actions, Terraform workflows
      - drift detection approach
   J) Cost & FinOps signals
      - tagging strategy, cost allocation, Savings Plans/RI/Spot usage, S3 lifecycle
      - high-cost services and likely waste (best-effort based on architecture)
   K) Resilience & DR
      - multi-AZ patterns, multi-region strategy, RTO/RPO, failover mechanisms

3) Produce diagrams in Mermaid:
   - Diagram 1: High-level system architecture (edge → networking → compute → data)
   - Diagram 2: Networking topology (VPCs/subnets/TGW/peering/PrivateLink)
   - Diagram 3: Security & governance (accounts/OUs/SCP/log archive/security tooling)
   - Diagram 4 (optional): Data platform flow (ingest → storage → processing → analytics)

4) Run a Well-Architected style review:
   - For each pillar (Ops Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance, Cost, Sustainability):
     - 3–8 key findings (prioritized)
     - recommended remediation actions
     - expected tradeoffs

5) Output a prioritized remediation plan:
   - P0 (critical security/reliability), P1, P2 improvements
   - include “quick wins” and “bigger refactors”
   - include a validation checklist and how to test changes safely

External Knowledge Requirement (Mandatory)
When referencing AWS service limits, defaults, security recommendations, pricing model behaviors, or best practices that may change, consult authoritative external sources (AWS docs, AWS whitepapers, AWS blog, AWS Well-Architected, or official GitHub repos) and cite them in reasoning notes. If browsing is not available, label items as “Needs external verification” and list exact search queries to run.

Constraints
- Do not invent resources not present in the provided files.
- Do not expose secrets. Redact any sensitive values found.
- Prefer accuracy over speculation. Clearly label assumptions.
- Provide actionable outputs: diagrams + checklist + plan.
- Keep outputs compatible with both small and enterprise setups.

Files to Inspect / Request
- Provide the repository paths that contain IaC (e.g., infra/terraform, modules, stacks).
- Optional: exports (terraform plan output, tfstate (sanitized), CloudTrail/SecurityHub findings export, account OU notes).

Output Format
1) Quick Summary (10–25 bullets)
2) Full Inventory (sections A–K)
3) Diagrams (Mermaid code blocks)
4) Well-Architected Findings (by pillar)
5) Risk Register (Security/Availability/Cost) prioritized
6) Remediation Plan (P0/P1/P2) with effort sizing
7) Validation Checklist
8) Needs External Verification (if any) + exact search queries

Reasoning Depth (NZT-48 Toggle)
NZT-48: ON (maximum rigor, consistency checks, no hallucinations)

Validation / Self-Check
- Confirm every inventory item is grounded in repo files or clearly marked as an assumption.
- Confirm diagrams represent the described components and relationships.
- Confirm no secret material is exposed.
- Confirm remediation plan is actionable and prioritized.